feat(ADR-CORE-061): implement Tiered Interrupt Architecture
This commit implements the Tiered Interrupt Architecture which separates
infrastructure concerns from semantic completion evaluation.

## Changes

### graph_orchestrator.py
- Add `classify_interrupt()` - Tier 1 procedural classifier (no LLM)
  - TERMINAL: user_abort → End
  - BENIGN: max_iterations, context_overflow → Facilitator (seamless continue)
  - PATHOLOGICAL: stagnation, tool_error → Interrupt Evaluator
  - NORMAL: artifacts → Exit Interview, no artifacts → Router
- Add `_detect_unrecovered_failures()` - trace failure detection
- Add `_detect_trace_stutter()` - semantic-chunker drift detection

### exit_interview_specialist.py
- REMOVE `_evaluate_trace_heuristics()` (moved to Interrupt Classifier)
- REMOVE `_detect_trace_stutter()` (moved to Interrupt Classifier)
- Exit Interview is now a PURE LLM semantic completion evaluator
- Only answers: "Is the task done?"

### test_interrupt_classifier.py
- Add comprehensive tests for all interrupt classifications
- Test priority ordering (TERMINAL > BENIGN > PATHOLOGICAL > NORMAL)

### test_exit_interview_specialist.py
- Remove obsolete heuristic tests (functionality moved)
- Add purity tests asserting Exit Interview has no heuristics
- Add LLM evaluation tests

## Architecture

The key insight: Not all interrupts are the same.

| Interrupt | Healthy Trace? | Response |
|-----------|----------------|----------|
| max_iterations | Yes | Seamless continue |
| stagnation | No (stuttering) | Needs correction |
| tool_error | Partial | Retry or escalate |
| user_abort | N/A | End |

This separates "Can this be saved?" (Interrupt Evaluator) from
"Is the task done?" (Exit Interview).

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.5 <noreply@anthropic.com>

