## Documentation Updates

**MCP_GUIDE.md:**
- Added Section 5.2: Advanced Pattern: Internal Iteration with MCP
- Contrasts graph-level looping (8 routing cycles) vs internal iteration (2 cycles)
- Shows complete BatchProcessorSpecialist example with MCP calls
- Explains architectural benefits and when to use this pattern

**CREATING_A_NEW_SPECIALIST.md:**
- Added "Advanced Pattern: Internal Iteration with MCP" section
- Step-by-step walkthrough of collection processing
- Benefits analysis and usage guidelines
- Testing examples for partial failures
- Links to complete implementation and tests

## Key Architectural Insights

**Problem Solved:**
User identified: "It seems tricky to get recommended_next_specialist to keep working through
a loop... probably impossible without a counter in scratchpad"

**Solution:**
- Use artifacts (persistent) not scratchpad (ephemeral) for iteration state
- More importantly: avoid graph-level iteration entirely via internal looping
- Graph sees single atomic operation, specialist iterates internally

**Benefits:**
- ✅ Atomic execution - All items processed in one graph node
- ✅ Emergent logic - LLM decides destinations (not hardcoded)
- ✅ Granular error handling - Continues on failures, tracks each item
- ✅ Rich observability - Decision rationale for each file
- ✅ No graph looping - Avoids routing complexity and overhead

**Use Cases:**
- Sorting/organizing multiple files
- Batch processing records with emergent logic
- Collection operations requiring LLM decisions per item

## Example Usage

User: "Sort these files into a-m/ and n-z/: e.txt, l.txt, n.txt, q.txt"

Router → BatchProcessor (single node):
  - Parse: ["e.txt", "l.txt", "n.txt", "q.txt"] + ["a-m/", "n-z/"]
  - LLM Plan: e→a-m, l→a-m, n→n-z, q→n-z
  - Execute: 4 file moves via MCP (internal loop)
  - Report: "Successfully sorted all 4 files."

